      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u help me study for my bio test? i need to understand the different stages of mitosis. can u just like, give me a step by step breakdown of what happens in each phase?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Sure, I'd be happy to help with that! Mitosis is divided into five main stages: Prophase, Prometaphase, Metaphase, Anaphase, and Telophase.\n\n1. In Prophase, the chromatin condenses into chromosomes, and each chromosome pairs with its identical sister. The nuclear membrane dissolves, and the mitotic spindle, made of microtubules, begins to form.\n2. During Prometaphase, the nuclear envelope completely disappears, and the chromosomes attach to the spindle fibers via their kinetochores.\n3. In Metaphase, the spindle fibers align all the chromosomes along the metaphase plate (the equator of the cell), ensuring that each new cell will receive an identical set of chromosomes.\n4. Anaphase starts when the sister chromatids (now considered individual chromosomes) are pulled apart by the spindle fibers and move toward opposite cell poles.\n5. Finally, in Telophase, the separated chromosomes reach the poles, a new nuclear membrane forms around each set of chromosomes, and the chromosomes begin to uncoil back into chromatin. The spindle fibers disperse, and cytokinesis (cell division) occurs, resulting in two daughter cells with identical genetic material",
      "source": "target",
